author: {'steamid': '76561199180006186', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 7, 'playtime_forever': 258, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 214, 'last_played': 1708564319}
review:
VRChat, is a good game, though don't be surprised to find a bunch of eight year olds screaming and whining. 

I've only played three hours of VRChat (At the time of me writing this), and have barely scratched the surface of this game, so don't think I know everything about this game, I don't. I've tried to avoid worlds that have stupid people on them, (mostly eight year olds) but it's incredibly hard. This game is great, though it has its pros and cons, so here are some that bother me:

SO many really young kids, who got a Quest 2 for their birthday, fooling their parents into letting them play VRChat. 

A LOT of LGBTQ+ members, I'm not being rude, I just know that I didn't expect it, so PARENTS be aware that this game isn't always made for kids. You will find two anime girls kissing on a balcony, or two dogs (Or ten) sleeping together. Even without the LGBTQ+ Members, this game still ISN'T made for kids, I joined a public world, and found a nude anime girl. It was literally the third world I went to, COUNTING the world you first spawn in. 

This game isn't awful, but it isn't amazing in my personal opinion. Now keep in mind, I HAVEN'T played the VR version of this game, I only play on my PC, so a lot of the awe that many have and talk about, I don't because I don't have to turn my in real life head, or move my hands, I can only walk around, talk, and dance.

Now I know I basically just shi# on this game so hard, but overall I'd still recommend this game to people of ages 16+.

author: {'steamid': '76561198965705666', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 22, 'playtime_forever': 12613, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 1806, 'playtime_at_review': 7689, 'last_played': 1712481898}
review:
I was going to rate this review yes, but I have decided against it. I have over 1000 hours on quest 2 and upgraded to pc recently. I wouldn't suggest anyone tries this game.

VR Chat has become very toxic over the past few years. I've had people crash me because I was either sad or not using a eboy/furry avatar in public lobbies. A portion of this community has also become way to comfortable with themselves. I've encountered countless people either ERPing or doing nasty shit like pissing on themselves or doing vore in giant avatars in public worlds where children are present while attempting to DDOS anyone who stands against them for their degeneracy. I have large list of gross personal VRC experiences.

The company itself also added Easy Anti-Cheat into the game, though this hasn't fixed any of the issues people have had with hackers and modders. If EAC worked then I wouldn't be blue screened by hackers because they think its funny. Aside from EAC, the company itself has a bad reputation with treatment of employees and every update just seems to be getting worse. 

While I have a lot of negatives, I will say this: you can meet a lot of cool people with interesting backgrounds. I've made friends with ex-military, emts, firefighters, a group dedicated to hunting pedophiles and even an ex-darkweb hacker that was looking to repent and taught me a bit about cyber security.

VRC is not a game I would recommend to anyone, especially anyone under 18 years old. Though if you do insist on trying the game I'll say this: make some friends and stick with them. Despite its flaws this is a game where you could make plenty of friends and become a legend in the community. Quite honestly this is a game where you need to experience it for a bit then decide whether you choose to stay. 

While I wouldn't recommend this to my friends and family, just remember; as a wise man once said, "You can't let one bad moment spoil a bunch of good ones." - Dale Earnhardt

review:
I was introduced to this game by a friend because I like to make stuff for games, this was supposed to be supportive of that hobby, which it kind of is but HOLY CRAP the sideload of absolute degenerate garbage that comes with it is almost not worth it. The depravity of mankind nearly eclipses our brilliance and I am not exaggerating. 
I don't even mind the kids, but as a mom myself I cannot fathom the levels of apathy or ignorance it takes a parent to let their kid roam in such a place without any regard to their safety. VRChat needs to make a separate age gated platform for these kids since their parents don't seem to GAF. Otherwise I do see eventually this getting shut down due to some legal trouble because the predators running around unchecked are AMOK. Try reporting someone, its not at all a streamlined process. 
VRChat is not the first of its kind, there have been other platforms that have promised the same thing, freedom of expression, creativity, creation, exploration and so on, and you know what doomed those platforms? Perversion, and unethical consumerism. P*rn addicted users get in and use the platform to indulge their habit just like drug junkies do, and scruple-less content creators sell things to them. EVERYONE ELSE GETS DRIVEN OUT. (If you are one of those users I encourage you to admit you have a problem, learn how this hurts you and those you love and seek help)
.
The developers and investors of VRChat have to determine if the income brought in by perversion is worth the short term gain, or if they even care that it will kill the platform in the long run. It's a devil's bargain. 
.
.
.
.
I am also so very sick of seeing anime avatars and hyper-sexualised anthropomorphic animals.

author: {'steamid': '76561198807404680', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 26, 'playtime_forever': 17083, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 17083, 'last_played': 1704857691}
review:
VRChat opens the door to an extraordinary and creative community of creators, offering limitless potential for unique experiences. Whether you're in VR or on desktop, it provides an entertaining way to connect with friends and immerse yourself in a myriad of user-generated content. But beware ‚Äì this game is a rabbit hole. Play too much, and you might find yourself down the path of acquiring VR gear, accessories, and potentially draining your wallet.

On the flip side, the developers' recent decisions and changes have raised concerns, hindering the community's creativity knowingly. It's disheartening to witness a platform that owes much of its success to the support of its community take steps that may dampen the very spirit that made it thrive. Despite the drawbacks, VRChat can still offer an enjoyable experience if played cautiously or for free.

In summary, VRChat provides a unique and fun-filled space, but recent developments in the hands of the developers might give players pause. Approach with caution or consider playing for free to fully enjoy the creative aspects without the potential drawbacks.

review: Definitely recommend this game for adults looking for a group to hang out with and have some fun here and there. However this game is most definitely not for kids no matter how much content is on here FOR kids, it should definitely 18+ or not allowed unsupervised. I've met some really bad people on this game that should never be in contact with children and the system can easily be bypassed for users who have been banned. I enjoy the game as a place to see long distance friends or to have good hangout without spending loads of money to go somewhere. But I even hate going into public lobbies because of the type of people I encounter. So just a tip to any parents wondering about the game, just..dont let your kid play it. For the sake of you and them.

author: {'steamid': '76561198264936099', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 3, 'playtime_forever': 1484, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 5, 'playtime_at_review': 1478, 'last_played': 1711661037}
review:
Light thumbs down, not a hard one.

At the time of writing, I don't have any VR equipment, so these impressions come from a strictly desktop perspective. The computer I played this on was outdated, but could run most 8th-gen games without issue, so I don't feel VRChat should have run poorly. I know the complexity of games isn't linear, but I don't see why this particular game should have run poorly for me, unless it was just lacking polish.

If you're looking at VRChat, you know roughly what you're in for. I'm giving it a thumbs down for technical issues rather than the culture of the game itself. How the community acts isn't the fault of the platform they use, but currently, VRChat as a platform still has great room for improvement.

Frankly, I don't enjoy much of VRChat culture, so my review DOES come with some bias- but it's not the deciding factor and I still had enough fun to stick with it for a little while. It was part of my rotation to a degree and I‚Äôve known people who absolutely love this game, so I've seen that it can be positive for people and see the appeal from a distance. If you don't care about the experience being sort of clunky and you're curious, go for it.

In my experience though, this game worked really poorly. I swear that every time I‚Äôd launch it, VRChat would hit me with a new minor bug. It had screen tearing all the time, completely stuttered at random points, would load just slowly enough to be annoying, I repeatedly had issues where my mouse was stuck scrolling in menus (couldn‚Äôt really navigate when this happened, only fix seemed to be restarting the game), I feel my mic worked especially poorly on this game.

I could get used to the interface but it wasn‚Äôt great either; there's potential to add a lot of keybind and HUD options that as far as I know don't exist, the menus would have been so much better with some size and speed adjustments and I really feel like the game didn‚Äôt have an overhaul to make the desktop experience much better. I'd give it a pass as being made for VR first, but this game has been around for so long that it feels lazy not to improve the desktop experience. Then I‚Äôve heard so many people talk about the developers neglecting this game and actively making it worse, I‚Äôm lead to believe it isn‚Äôt just the desktop experience that kind of sucks.

The options that were there also weren‚Äôt very thorough, so I didn‚Äôt feel I could do much about my nitpicks with the interface. If you aren't using a mic then the chatbox is really rudimentary too, leaving you stuck in place while you type and you're just forced to exit the chatbox and abandon your message if you want to move at all. As far as I know, there isn't even something like a little ping to alert you of new chatbox messages, nor built in text-to-speech, you just have to see when they're there.
You also have people using avatars that force crashes- I didn‚Äôt deal with them since I generally kept default avatars up- and it's inevitable for things like that to be on a platform like this, but also very obvious that Easy Anti-Cheat doesn't do much for VRChat. With some things I wasn‚Äôt sure whether it was the game or user-generated content that had an issue, notably, I would sometimes be flying around randomly when I entered some of my regular maps.

You might wonder why I bothered playing this game, since I had no VR equipment and often engaged with the chatbox rather than mic. Well, first of all, I saw plenty of people who used a mix of VR and desktop, or mic and chatbox- improving the desktop experience and chatbox would help those people, too.
More to the point, to reiterate, there's still fun to be had. It's pretty obvious that the main appeal of this game is how wacky it can get- though it was a double-edged sword for me. Mostly tiring. It‚Äôs one of the reasons I quit. But my favorite worlds on VRChat were the "chill" maps designed to sit in, talk, maybe play some music and people have made a few that are genuinely quite nice. It's always good to have more ways I can interact with the people I already care about, we could express ourselves uniquely with avatars and it's free.

VRChat's culture is a matter of personal preference and beyond that I think your enjoyment rests on how much you connect with the tools to express yourself here. I feel like I've seen the same brand of edginess in, say, plenty of Discord servers and a lot of people just aren't responsive or are only getting inebriated (which I find very unpleasant)- all things considered, it doesn't feel very different from many spaces on the Internet- but if you find good people to wander or just chat with, this can be a uniquely cool platform.

author: {'steamid': '76561199021643544', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 3, 'playtime_forever': 18718, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 3472, 'playtime_at_review': 3929, 'last_played': 1712461372}
review:
As someone deciding to play without the VR Headset, VRChat is still a really good social game despite the less immersive experience. Although you are more limited on how you are able to interact with the virtual world around you, if you want a good social experience regardless of how you are playing, pick this one up. The game offers endless ways to express yourself, socialize with your peers, and is overall a good time when you have some free time. And if you decide that you want to try out a VR Headset, it does make it more like you are physically there, but it‚Äôs not a necessary accessory for overall enjoyment. Anyone can play VRChat. It‚Äôs not restricted to just a headset.

However do be aware that yes, ANYONE can play VRChat. You don‚Äôt know who you are talking to behind the avatar, so stay vigilant. Because (at the time of writing this) the game is free on Steam, anyone can play without a VR Headset. Remember that if you feel uncomfortable with another user, you are allowed to block them, report them, or leave. You aren‚Äôt obligated to stay for a chat. There are many legitimately nice people who frequent the game as well as the opposite. Please do be careful about who you decide to become friends with.

You're going to see some beautiful things in here, you're also going to see some... questionable things too. Just don't question it. I know this review might not be so helpful, but allow me to boil it down to pros and cons:

[b]Pros: It is a physical manifestation of the internet where anyone can create ANYTHING[/b]
[b]Cons: It is a physical manifestation of the internet where anyone can create ANYTHING[/b]

author: {'steamid': '76561198151389599', 'num_games_owned': 103, 'num_reviews': 1, 'playtime_forever': 129551, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 129551, 'last_played': 1706676054}
review:
PARENTS, DO NOT LET YOUR KIDS JOIN THIS GAME!
This review is more about the community rather than the content of the game. I have joined this game back in late 2020 where the COVID environment was still rampant. During this time, most of the places I went to be social were closed and being a social person myself, I required an outlet to talk to others. I have logged in over 2000 hours in this game (not including on oculus, i mean meta). What I first enjoyed about this game is that I met so many people who had similar interests as I do, more than any other social gathering I have participated. To which at a point, like many others, started to get absorbed into this community. I would give this community credit in my interest in computers and understanding the hardware which gave me the ability to build 2 of them. Also meeting people from this community had me find who played similar games as I do and had game meet ups to play. This game allowed people to be creative and self taught for technology,  3D modeling, world building, game design, community building, and overall exchange of different cultural backgrounds. I have made lasting relationships with people on this game and I will never forget them. 
Now, you see that I have a disagreeable opinion on this game. The problem is, when you have a program that allows anyone to play this game, is that anyone can play this game, especially when there are those who cause more harm than good. I have witnessed many unethical practices in this game that would even have our political leaders question of what kind of society that they are leading. I can summarize this game into one phrase: this is virtual high school. Where you have kids running around saying the "N" word without consequence (getting banned isn't a real consequence), where adults act like kids and have behavior that I would send people to a psych ward. Unfortunately, toxic behavior is somehow praised and continues to build through out this community. Apparently having mental issues is something to be proud of like wearing a badge of pride. I have seen people get so absorbed into this game that they sacrifice their personal lives, dedicate and invest thousands of dollars into this game (especially to those who don't have the financial means to support themselves. this is a strong portion of the people who participate in this game). I have seen narcissists who believe everything that comes out their mouths and people who are dumb enough to follow them. Having a game that allows kids to socialize with adults, allows pedophiles to groom and commit unforgivable acts (there are groups who gather pedophiles to promote their horrific acts). Alcoholism runs rampant in this game. Parents neglect their kids to play this game. Basically people sell their soul for this game. I wouldn't call the people in this game a cult (I would not be surprised if there were cults in this game) but it changes people to the point where their original personality disappears. Just like comments in videos and social media, it does allow people to treat others awfully while hiding behind their screens and VR headsets. I could write a whole review of relationships alone of how bad it gets. Cheating is a norm for VR relationships. Having multiple or poly relationships is the norm. Running from relationship to relationship is the norm. People using "love" as an excuse where these people have no idea what love is. This VR marriage is something beyond my mind that I cannot comprehend. This game is full of people that were high school losers that got no attention and now having that social status let that power run in their heads and now think they are god's greatest gift to earth. I for one know that I am not a perfect person (far from it) but surrounding myself with these people showed that I can do better and walking away from this environment would be the best move. Good luck to those who play this game and hopefully you have the self esteem to realize that you deserve friends who treat you with kindness (Trust me, they are from few and far between).

author: {'steamid': '76561198058089029', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 26, 'playtime_forever': 7597, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 7597, 'last_played': 1702824592}
review:
VRChat is my top recommendation for anyone stepping into VR. The community truly defines this game, and the developers' incredible flexibility never ceases to amaze me. However, the platform is starting to show its age, particularly in terms of user-generated content and maintaining player engagement. As a social game, VRChat currently seems to attract a large number of introverts, and as one myself, I find this both comforting and limiting. The community is somewhat divided between those with access to certain content or skills (the "haves") and those without (the "have nots"), creating a social dynamic that, unfortunately, makes the community feel less open than it aspires to be.

Despite these challenges, VRChat's support for a wide array of playstyles and its accommodation for a diverse user base are truly commendable. The creativity and fun generated by its users are awe-inspiring. It's hard not to appreciate the vastness of experiences available, from exploring different worlds to participating in unique activities. The creativity and dedication of the community make it a vibrant place where so much enjoyment and innovation happen.

author: {'steamid': '76561198278440288', 'num_games_owned': 93, 'num_reviews': 4, 'playtime_forever': 56522, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 56522, 'last_played': 1703050991}
review:
After five or so years of playing VRChat, I think it's about time I made a proper review. I really started playing it during the covid outbreak, and during that time I met a lot of really cool people, some of which I still call friends to this day. It helped me work through my social anxiety, which in turn helped bring about a lot of my success in high school and is still helping me now.

That being said, there was a point where I was *too* invested into the game, and adding on top of that problems with mental health, you don't get a pretty scene. Depending on the groups or people you interact with it can be a cesspool of hate and drama. Plus, I was going into it with a toxic mentality about myself, which only adds to the problem.

So I took a bit of a break and worked my problems out irl. After getting to a stable point in my mental health, I went back into the game with a new mindset and goal; to have fun with my friends and talk to strangers. Fast forward a year or so, and here we are. I'm off my medication, doing well in college, and have never felt better!

Too much of anything will be bad for you, whether it be junk food, sleep, even water, and of course VRChat. Play the game in moderation and know what you are playing it for, or else you could find yourself in a bad place.

I owe a lot of the good things that I have going for me irl to this game and all that I learned from it, so overall, I'd say it's pretty good if you use it properly! :>



Tl;dr: VRC is a fun game that helped me with social anxiety and other mental problems, just make sure to play it in moderation or else the game could become apart of your problems.

author: {'steamid': '76561198071872990', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 1, 'playtime_forever': 9634, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 377, 'playtime_at_review': 7512, 'last_played': 1712239351}
review:
Disclaimer: I've only played desktop mode because I'm unemployed and broke and my room is tiny.

Has been a boon to my ability to express myself online that has genuinely helped me grow as a person. Runs on fairly modest hardware if one is sensible with how many avatars one enables, although it still has an absolute craving for memory (because people keep uploading models with bajillions of polygons) and some memory leak issues.

Life pro tip: disable shaders on all trust ranks. User-submitted models with user-written shaders + graphics drivers that are continuously needing updates to fix bugs = you're gonna have a bad time (e.g. your system may hard lock on you, and if your OS/driver setup doesn't automatically reset itself you'll need to power cycle your computer). This isn't a vrchat problem so much as it's just what is bound to happen, because graphics drivers can't test for every vrchat model that ever existed.

If you can cope with these flaws I would definitely recommend the game.

Easy Anti Cheat is probably the worst thing they have ever "Added" to VRC.
No proper modding support that won't get you banned.

The good,

You can find some cool ass people from all walks of life that you can actually learn from.
It's a great place for people that have communication issues and wish remedy that on their own terms.
It's also a great place for creators that wish to work with unity however I hear the SKD is sometimes a pain in the ass.

Summery,

DON'T LET YOU CHILDREN ON HERE!! It's not a great alternative to a daycare! 
I would personally say that VRC should only be 18+, it's full of degenerates and pedophiles and people that just wish to take advantage of you. 
Be careful.

author: {'steamid': '76561197970647767', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 12, 'playtime_forever': 16253, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 26, 'playtime_at_review': 16227, 'last_played': 1711309366}
review:
VRChat is the social application with far the most users and which supports a lot of platforms.
Since it has now also opened to a broader audience with mobile- and desktop-support, it has a strongly growing user-base.

Pros: 

- The userinterface has evolved a lot over the years and can be considered a "standard" already, as it allows layered configurations using a simple- and an advanced mode.

- It has the best avatar-support so far, since it has a lot of options for motion-capturing, eye-tracking, importing etc.

- There are too many levels to download and visit. There are tens of thousands of them, and you can probably not visit them all already.  The quality is very varying, though. As usually with UGC, a lot is low quality.
But then again, often, you can get very surprised when you suddenly find a new graphical gem or a well executed game or theater.

Cons:

- Lighting-support is unfortunately limited. Characters do not receive light and do not have self-shadowing or use advanced shaders, and pointlights are as far as I know not importable at all. This reduces overall possible graphics quality the most and is inferior to other social apps

- Avatars are seperated into three performance-categories "low/mid/high". The avatars you can find are mostly on high though, so that on default-settings, your "fallback-avatar" will be shown for others, which makes them often pointless.  

- Performance can be too low sometimes. I believe it may have to do with the engine and not always with the user generated content

- There is no way to teleport to a user in a level

- You need to find friends first in order to be able to join "groups", in order to be able to join "events". It would be better. if you could see all events on a "global event table", with notifications. Currently, events are spread over a lot of custom discord servers

- Youtube support is often buggy and limited especially on mobile platforms if it comes to synchronization. Broadcasting desktop can be done, but has a high latency and is not working consistently. Otherwise, it could be used for other usecases.

A lot of games or "game-objects" work very well like billard or bowling which I would consider polished enough to be sold as a seperate game, and other games are rather basic, but are fun in multiplayer.  A lot to investigate.

VRChat is in its state what you could consider to be the metaverse the most. 

Personally I do not get really warm with the avatars. It may have to do with the lighting, or is a personal preference. Often, the characters look too "cartoonish" for me.
But there are also exceptions. Some avatars are great, so it may have to do with the availability as well.

author: {'steamid': '76561199230755343', 'num_games_owned': 188, 'num_reviews': 18, 'playtime_forever': 6964, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 450, 'playtime_at_review': 6909, 'last_played': 1712272806}
review:
Just as a "software?" VRChat is okay, 
it's nothing special when it comes to controls or
interacting with the environment.
You can walk/run, jump,
look around and select things to
either grab and let go or
use things such as chairs, pretty basic.

But as a game it's wonderful,
there are all kinds of worlds you can explore,
there are games remade inside this game,
you can appear to people as anything you want to be by choosing an Avatar,
as long as what you're looking for is available.

Since almost all these worlds and avatars are made by the community, 
they are not all the same,
some are boring while some are absolutely breathtaking.
You can expect most worlds to be small but there are big worlds also,
the biggest a world can be is 20x20km.

Your game satisfaction truly depends on the kind of world you join and the people you meet.

author: {'steamid': '76561198042109534', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 5, 'playtime_forever': 85261, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 2539, 'playtime_at_review': 78120, 'last_played': 1712288635}
review:
There's something special about discussing college experiences with a 12 foot tall werewolf.

VRChat is by nature going to be a buggy, obnoxious platform to hang out it. Very often you get technical issues that make enjoying the game very difficult to enjoy or you find out your hardware is just never going to cut it. Further, it's a social platform and that means you're going to get obnoxious people. I feel that it doesn't matter how much work the VRChat team puts into their work, these are two constants that cannot be changed, and I'm okay with that.

For me, VRChat started out as a place to relax when my arms hurt too much from Beat Saber, but over time it's become my primary social platform. I've learned so much about technical 3D things that I never would have been able to experience if this platform didn't exist, and I've made countless friends along the way.

I enjoy this platform and I hope that both the community and the development team can continue to build this amazing place together.
